<HEAD>
<TITLE>Computer Piracy</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>Computer Piracy</H1>
<BR>
<B>Author:</B>  Jerry Lee<BR>
<B>Email:</B><I>  eauu392@ea.oac.uci.edu</I>
<HR>
<BR>
<H2>Introduction</H2>
<BR>
     <P>There are many different kinds of thievery in our
society; most noticeable are the stealing of merchandise,
money, or anything else of value.  However, with the rise of
high-tech computers in the 80's and 90's, a new kind of crime
emerged along with it.  The act of stealing computer
software, known as piracy, has been growing out of proportion
in the past few years.  As a result of this, software
companies are losing billions of dollars in lost revenue
every year for which the legitimate consumer ultimately
suffers with higher prices.  Many attempts were made by both
the government and software companies to counter this trend,
but to no avail.  Time is running out and as our world
economy becomes increasingly dependent on information and
technology, protecting intellectual property is essential for
our future.  In this paper, I will explore the world of
computer piracy along with possible solutions for resolving it.</P>
<HR>
<BR>
<H2>Definition</H2>
<BR>
     <P>Computer piracy, by definition, is the unauthorized
duplication of computer software.  It can occur when a person
purchases software and duplicates it in order to give it to
their friends, relatives, or whomever.  That person can then
make more copies and give it to their friends which
perpetuates this ongoing cycle.  Another way in which
unauthorized distribution takes place is through illegal
computer bulletin board services (BBS) that distribute
hundreds of copyrighted commercial software as well as
pornography and other censored material.  Computer piracy
does not only occur between private friends and BBS's, but
also through corporate sites where an enormous number of
pirated software is distributed.</P>
<BR>
<UL>
<LI><A 
HREF="http://www.digital.com/gnn/bus/hewm/intellectual_property.html">Software as intellectual property</A>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.portal.com/~cyberlaw/cylw894.html">Software 
Patents</A>
<LI><A 
HREF="http://gnv.ifas.ufl.edu/WWW/PIRATE/RESOURCE.HTM#part2">Software 
Copyright Resources</A>
</UL> 
<HR>
<BR>
<H2>How has it come this far?</H2>
<BR>
     <P>The reason that computer piracy has become so big is
because it is so easy to get away with.  First of all, it
only takes a computer and an inexpensive blank disk in order
to duplicate the particular software for distribution.
Second, since the information on diskettes are recorded
digitally, the precision and integrity of the software's code
is always perfect.  Digital information can be copied at no
cost and with practically no detection since the 1000th copy
made of a particular software will be indistinguishable from
the original.</P>
<HR>
<BR>
<H2>Facts and Figures</H2>
<BR>
     <P>It is estimated that the software industry lost more
than $12.8 billion due to piracy with $2.2 billion in the
U.S.  alone according to the Business Software Alliance.
They also estimate that 35% of the total software in the U.S.
may be illegal, 80% in Japan, and an incredible 99% in Thailand.
With staggering figures like these, the software companies have
no other choice but to raise the prices on their software in
order to make up for the lost revenue.</P>
<HR>
<BR>
<H2>Legal Issues</H2>
<BR>
     <P>Stopping computer piracy or even controlling piracy
alone is a very difficult task as it was evident in the past
events.  At first, the government proposed and passed
different kinds of laws discouraging computer piracy.
According to the U.S. Copyright Law, computer piracy is a
federal offense and civil damages can be as much as $50,000
or more and criminal penalties include fines and
imprisonment.  This may seem like a pretty tough law, but
unfortunately people ignore it because computer piracy is
very easy to get away with.  Consequently, the government got
specific by passing a legislation that made
possessing ten unauthorized copies of a software program a
felony.</P>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/usc/17/overview.html">Copyright 
Act of 1976</A>
<LI><A 
HREF="gopher://isaac.engr.washington.edu/0R54109-56869-/arch/usenet/comp.os.os2.announce/Comp.os.os2.announce.9411">Reward for information about piracy</A>
<LI><A 
HREF="http://gnv.ifas.ufl.edu/WWW/PIRATE/POLICY.HTM#part1">Software 
Copyright Policies and Guidelines</A></UL> 

<HR>
<BR>
<H2>Past Failed Attempts</H2>
<BR>
<P>With new laws proving to be
ineffective, software developers tried to counter computer
piracy by developing a technique called 'copy-protection'.
They tried to outsmart software thieves by either altering
tracks on the diskette in order to make it harder to
duplicate or making the software perform 'document checks' in
which the program requests particular information from the
owner's manual of the software in order to run the program.
This would insure that the person currently running the
program is the legitimate owner.  This also eventually became
a futile attempt by software companies; highly skilled
computer hackers used their knowledge to remove the copy-
protection.  After all of this, it is evident that new strict
laws by the government nor schemes to outsmart potential
thieves by the software industry do not intimidate the
hackers any bit.</P>
<HR>
<BR>
<H2>Roots to the problem</H2>
<BR>
     <P>When trying to resolve computer piracy, you must first
look at the roots that contribute to it.  In analyzing the
causes of computer piracy that I have already mentioned,
it can be broken down to two main factors.
First, one source of computer piracy is between private
citizens (between friends and BBS's). Second, another main
source of computer piracy occurs on corporate sites.  </P>
<HR>
<BR>
<H2>Ethics and Moral Issues</H2>
<BR>
     <P>Computer piracy is very common among private citizens.
people can make copies for their friends, family, or just
about anyone.  Unfortunately, many people innocently feel
that they are doing nothing wrong by making a few copies for
their friends.  They do not realize that they are not only
doing a disservice to themselves by breaking the law, but
also by causing everyone to suffer from the increase in
prices on future software.  When
a consumer legally purchases a piece of software from a
vendor, there is a contract that exists between the software
company and the consumer.  Most people believe that once they
have purchased software,
they own it.  This is not quite true.  In fact, what has been
purchased is the license allows the purchaser to use the
product.  The software company still owns the software.  This
lack of understanding often leads to breaches of contract
through software piracy, and in many cases the pirates are
not even aware of the illegalities of their actions.  We must
also understand that there is a mutual trust between the
consumer and the software developer; "the consumer trusts that
the software developer will develop the best possible
software along with the fairest prices and the software
developer trusts that the consumer will use the software only
in the manner for which they have purchased it" and will not
make any unauthorized copies.(SPA)</P>
<UL>
