Copyright Training Materials</A>

</UL> 

<HR>
<BR>
<H2>Possible Solutions?</H2>
<BR>
     <P>We must educate the consumers, here and abroad, on the
legal and ethical issues of computer piracy.  Although a lot
of attention is given to the new computer technology,
computer piracy is rarely addressed in the media or in the
educational institutions.  Raising the public's awareness
about computer piracy is a very realistic proposal
and can be executed without much hassle.  One prime example
who are already executing this plan are the two major anti-
piracy organizations: Business Software Alliance (BSA) and
Software Publishers Association (SPA).  One objective for
both the BSA and the SPA is education; they want the public
to understand what computer piracy is.  In order to do this,
these organizations have printed numerous brochures about
piracy and also made public messages on television to inform
the public about what is going on.  The SPA have also set up
a 1-800# for the public in which they can call with questions
dealing with piracy and its legalities.  I believe that the
government can also take part in this by making publicized
messages on television/radio and even implement them through
education in the schools.  These are both good means of
getting the message out to the public.</P>
     <P>In dealing with big corporations about computer piracy,
I think that actions and litigation must be put forth against
them.  Non-profit organization such as the SPA are the
leading groups that help litigate and convict corrupt
corporations.  These SPA alone filed 245 lawsuits for illegal
software copying, had 332 cease and desist orders issued, had
577 organizations targeted for investigation, and fined $3.6
million in total fines to corporate sites in 1993 alone
(Brandel 12).  With these numbers, we can see that the SPA
has done a substantial job into fighting piracy for a single
organization.</P>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="gopher://una.hh.lib.umich.edu/00/ebb/soft/soft9309.008">BSA 
(Business Software Alliance)</A>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.express-systems.com/csminfo.htm">SPA (Software 
Publishers Association)</A>
</UL>

 <HR>
<BR>
<H2>And the Rest of the World?</H2>
<BR>
     <P>Even if the United States succeeds in the fight against
piracy, the rest of the world still remains a big problem.
Computer piracy is even worse in Asia, Europe, and other
parts of the world.  In some countries, laws do not exist in
which the unauthorized duplication of copyrighted material is
prohibited.  Even though 80% of all the software in the world
is from the United States, we cannot simply act as the "world
police" and enforce its own laws on other countries.  I
believe that the U.S. government should get involved and try
to communicate with the governments of other countries in
order to help prevent piracy abroad.  We should encourage
foreign countries to enforce its copyright laws if they do
have one and establish copyright laws if they don't have one.</P>

</B>Other foreign countries and their laws:
